<tbody>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"row"><strong>x </strong></th>
<td><strong>1 </strong></td>
<td><b>3</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"row"><strong>y</strong></th>
<td><strong>2</strong></td>
<td><b>0.5 </b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>So we have 2 points A (1, 2) and B (3, 0.5).</p>
<p>Similarly, find at least two values of x and y satisfying the equation -=
x + 2y =3D 3</p>
<table border=3D"1">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"row"><strong>x </strong></th>
<td><b>-3 </b></td>
<td><b>3 </b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"row"><strong>y</strong></th>
<td><b>0</b></td>
<td><b>3</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>We have two points C(-3, 0) and D( 3, 3).<br>
Plotting these points on the graph we can get the lines in a coordinate pla=
ne as shown below.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Solving Linear Equations in Two Variables " src=3D"https://d=
138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/solving-linear-equatio=
ns-in-two-variables-using-graph-1619704648.png" style=3D"width: 400px;"></p=
>
<p>We observe that the two <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/inte=
rsection-of-two-lines/">lines intersect</a> at (1, 2). So, x =3D 1, y =3D 2=
 is the solution of given system of equations. Methods I and II are the alg=
ebraic way of solving simultaneous equations and III is the <a href=3D"http=
s://www.cuemath.com/algebra/graphically-solving-a-pair-of-linear-equations/=
">graphical method</a>.</p>
<h3>Solving System of Equations Using Cross-multiplication method</h3>
<p>In this method, we solve the systems of equations a<sub>1</sub>x + b<sub=
>1</sub>y + c<sub>1</sub> =3D 0 and a<sub>2</sub>x + b<sub>2</sub>y + c<sub=
>2</sub> =3D 0 using the cross-multiplication formula:</p>
<p>x / (b<sub>1</sub>c<sub>2</sub> - b<sub>2</sub>c<sub>1</sub>) =3D -y / (=
a<sub>1</sub>c<sub>2</sub> - a<sub>2</sub>c<sub>1</sub>) =3D 1 / (a<sub>1</=
sub>b<sub>2</sub> - a<sub>2</sub>b<sub>1</sub>)</p>
<p>For more detailed information of this method, click <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.cuemath.com/algebra/cross-multiplication-method/">here</a>.</p>
